president bushs choice to lead the national 
endowment for the arts says a measure by sen jesse helms to stop 
federal funding of sexually explicit or blasphemous art would 
cripple the governments role in promoting artistic excellence 
making unfettered artistic judgments would be most difficult 
under the helms amendment john e frohnmayer told a senate 
committee considering his nomination 
i think we need freedom and tolerance for art to 
flourish the portland ore lawyer told the senate labor and 
human resources committee on friday 
the arts agency is at the center of a political storm resulting 
from the use of federal money in exhibits that included works by 
artists robert mapplethorpe and andres serrano mapplethorpes 
photographs depict explicit homosexual acts and serrano displayed a 
work showing a crucifix submerged in a jar of urine 
the senate in july adopted an amendment by helms rnc that 
would prohibit the agency from using any of its 170 million in 
annual appropriations to promote distribute or produce obscene 
and indecent materials or art that denigrates the beliefs of any 
religion 
the house voted against helms measure 264153 last week after 
endowment defenders complained it would establish a broad pattern of 
censorship that would destroy the agencys credibility in the arts 
community 
the endowment uses panels of experts to award subsidies each year 
to artists 
i do not believe in funding obscene art frohnmayer said 
but he added i would certainly hate to see the whole structure 
change because of some grants which are controversial 
a onetime divinity student with a graduate degree in christian 
ethics from the university of chicago frohnmayer encountered no 
opposition to his confirmation from members of the senate committee 
if approved by the full senate he would replace hugh southern 
who has been named general manager of the new york metropolitan 
opera 
