<TEXT>
a federal advisory committee says the worlds 
leading sleep medication halcion may put users at greater risk of 
temporary amnesia than other drugs of its kind 
the food and drug administration panel recommended friday that 
the warning be added to halcions label and that stronger warnings 
be given to consumers and doctors about all possible side effects 
for this drug and other sedativehypnotics which are sold only by 
prescription 
the psychopharmacological drugs advisory committee asked the fda 
to work out the language of the warnings paul leber director of 
the fdas division of neuropharmacological drug products said it 
would be at least six months before the agency would complete work 
on the warnings 
theres no sense of urgency on this he said 
godfrey grant a spokesman for the upjohn co which makes 
halcion said the committees review should put to rest many 
concerns that have been raised about the drug 
the recommendations resulted from the committees review of a 
relatively high number of reports about side effects associated 
with the use of halcion compared with other sedativehypnotics 
these included amnesia anxiety aggression and hallucinations all 
of which are included in the warning label for halcion 
panel members said the high number of reactions reported may be 
overstated since incomplete data on incidents was collected and it 
can be used only as a broad indicator 
given the limitations of the information we did not sense 
there was a special problem of side effects with halcion said dr 
daniel e casey panel chairman and chief of psychiatric research 
and psychopharmacology at the veterans administration medical center 
in portland ore 
halcion was approved for sale in the united states in 1983 and 
about 43 million prescriptions of the drug have been written since 
then the fda has received 1693 reports of adverse side effects 
possibly associated with its use ranging from amnesia to death 
said charles anello deputy director of the fdas office of 
epidemiology and biostatistics 
by comparison 35 million prescriptions have been written for 
restoril a sedativehypnotic made by sandoz pharmaceuticals corp 
since 1981 and the fda has received 266 reports of unwanted side 
effects he said 
officials of the upjohn co which makes halcion said the 
greater number of halcion reports could be the result of a number of 
things including media reports about the drug these include 
reports about a utah woman shot her mother last year after taking 
halcion charges against the woman were dismissed 
upjohn spokesman grant said the company was pleased the 
advisory committee has essentially come to the conclusion that there 
are few if any concerns that need to be addressed 
besides agreeing to recommend relabeling for halcion for 
temporary amnesia the panel decided to address concerns for the 
entire class of sleeping pills three drugs are included in this 
class halcion restoril and dalmane 
panel members asked the fda to provide material to consumers to 
alert them to the possibility of side effects of the drugs so the 
consumers could discuss them with their doctors 
committee members said they were concerned about travelers 
amnesia a temporary syndrome that can affect travelers who take 
one of the drugs they can function normally after awakening but 
later wont recall their activities during this period such as 
going through customs at the airport 
the labels for these drugs already warn of amnesia as a possible 
side effect but the committee recommended the fda consider adding 
travelers amnesia to the labels 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

