<TEXT>
irving berlin created the american popular song 
until berlin began writing after the turn of the century 
american music was dominated by europe english music hall gilbert 
and sullivan viennese operetta and italian opera berlin took 
native american sounds such as ragtime and turned them into huge 
popular hits like alexanders ragtime band and everybodys 
doin it now when irving berlin wrote america listened for 
more than 50 years 
he caught the voices of the people early in this century and 
held them for longer than anyone else robert kimball musical 
theater historian said friday 
from his first song marie of sunny italy in 1907 to his 
last broadway show mr president in 1962 berlins presence 
was felt on the music scene in this country no one today can look 
to such a long period of domination 
and berlin was a winner in every medium he tried he found 
success not only in tin pan alley but on broadway with musicals like 
annie get your gun call me madam and his music box revues 
and in hollywood where he wrote the scores for fred astaireginger 
rogers movies like top hat and follow the fleet and other 
films like holiday inn and easter parade 
his colleagues thought he was the best particularly 
contemporaries like jerome kern he had an enormous influence on the 
broadway composers who followed him especially george gershwin and 
harold arlen who relished his inventive way with rhythm 
berlin also had an incredible versatility a great intelligence 
and perspective about the world he could write any kind of song a 
stirring patriotic anthem like god bless america a seasonal 
standard like white christmas a comic theater ditty like 
doin what comes naturlly an unbashedly sentimental favorite 
like always or a complex love song like lets face the music 
and dance 
he was a folk singer and he was able to absorb whatever was 
happening in the street and bring it out even more than stephen 
foster said edward jablonski a good friend of berlins and the 
author of several books on american theater composers he was an 
ordinary man who was able to write songs thats why he appealed so 
much to people 
but he also made a point of not being a welleducated musician 
he was a born musician which is a hard thing to be so he could be 
more sophisticated that he ever thought he was 
berlin also was a shrewd businessman he was a charter member and 
served on the first board of directors for ascap the american 
society of composers authors and publishers which collects 
songwriting royalties before 1920 he had formed his own music 
publishing company which published all of his music and at the time 
of his death he was still coowner of the music box theater a 
broadway theater he built in 1921 as late as two years ago he 
would call up the box office at the music box to see how the grosses 
were going 
but it will be for his music that he will be remembered 
i would think irving berlin is the most admired songwriter 
america has produced in this century and maybe ever kimball 
said 
</TEXT>
