<TEXT>
less than two years after the united 
states withdrew from cambodia khmer rouge guerrillas swept in from 
the bush to unleash one of the most barbaric revolutions of modern 
times 
this month as vietnam withdraws troops that have propped up the 
communist government the khmer rouge again are poised to strike 
from the jungles and many fear that cambodia will again become the 
land of the killing fields 
led by a ruthless communist with the alias of pol pot the khmer 
rouge withstood massive us bombing and won the cambodian war with 
probably no more than 60000 fighters in 1975 their opponents the 
government of usbacked gen lon nol fielded 300000 men 
the ratio is roughly the same today khmer rouge strength is 
estimated at 30000 to 40000 and phnom penhs at about 150000 
while there are new power brokers in phnom penh the top khmer 
rouge leadership remains unchanged although the 61yearold pol pot 
claimed he resigned from his last official post in june he still is 
believed to be in firm command 
the secretive guerrilla chief who has refused interviews for 10 
years spends his time along the thaicambodian border and in china 
the key khmer rouge arms supplier 
other durable veterans are pol pots righthand man ieng sary and 
nominal khmer rouge head khieu samphan whose doctoral thesis was 
the blueprint for a bloody agrarian revolution 
heading the khmer rouge army is son sen who approved the grisly 
tortures and executions of 20000 alleged dissidents at phnom penhs 
tuol sleng prison during the 197578 reign of terror another key 
commander is ta mok known as the butcher for his murderous ways 
these men have admitted to only some mistakes and claim to 
have changed policies and methods 
after being driven from phnom penh by a vietnamese invasion in 
january 1979 the khmer rouge operated from bases along the rugged 
thaicambodian frontier from there its leaders announced they had 
shed radical communism in favor of private property freedom of 
religion and a nonaligned foreign policy 
it was a dramatic shift one met by instant skepticism in their 
heydey the khmer rouge had cleansed the old society by killing 
hundreds of thousands driving buddhist monks from their monasteries 
and turning cambodia into a slave labor camp where even knives and 
forks were considered communal property 
no mass executions have been reported in khmer rougecontrolled 
areas since 1979 but defectors international aid workers and human 
rights groups indicate life under the khmer rouge remains slavelike 
beatings and occasional executions are meted out for violating 
decrees women and youngsters are conscripted as porters for the 
military and forced at times to trek through minefields religious 
worship is permitted only at showcase camps contact with foreigners 
is severely restricted to the point of denying the gravely ill 
medical treatment offered by aid agencies 
perhaps the most damning testimony comes from prince norodom 
sihanouk noncommunist leader of a threeparty guerrilla resistance 
that includes the khmer rouge 
one has to be either naive or an idiot to believe that the 
khmer rouge of the 80s can be different from the khmer rouge of the 
70s he has said 
the khmer rouge a term coined by sihanouk meaning red 
cambodians emerged in the 1960s and began its armed struggle in 
1968 as the war in neighboring vietnam was reaching a climax 
with ideology borrowed from mao tsetung and french leftists and 
with support from vietnams communists and a segment of cambodias 
rural population the small ragged band quickly grew into a 
movement its initial appeal sprang from real grievances of the 
peasantry and centuries of humiliation by cambodias more powerful 
neighbors 
on april 17 1975 phnom penh fell and its more than 2 million 
people were forced at gunpoint to march into the countryside and 
plant rice under appalling conditions 
for the victors it was year zero the remaking of society 
from scratch for most of cambodias 8 million people it was the 
beginning of an agony that lasted three years eight months and 20 
days 
the defeated khmer rouge army and its civilian followers 
straggled to the thai border in 1979 sapped by malaria hunger and 
hanois juggernaut it appeared pol pots days were numbered 
but the khmer rouge was saved by geopolitics and international 
relief aid the united states china noncommunist southeast asia 
and others were eager to bring vietnam to its knees and the khmer 
rouge was the most readily available instrument 
china provided weapons thailand allowed the use of its territory 
and the majority of un member states vote year after year to 
include the khmer rouge as part of the sihanouk coalition to 
represent cambodia at the world body 
critics charge this is the moral equivalent of inviting hitler to 
sit in the united nations after world war ii and western aid 
officials struggle with the fact that they kept what some call a 
monster alive by continuing food medical and other aid along the 
thaicambodian border 
after 11 years of war and the breakdown of peace talks the khmer 
rouge faces a new turning point 
with hanois soldiers still on the way out the khmer rouge and 
phnom penh forces already are testing each other in a major battle 
for the the gemrich border town of pailin 
western analysts regard the khmer rouge as the strongest of the 
three guerrilla factions and probably tougher than the governments 
sovietsupplied army 
the khmer rouge in the last three months controls much more 
territory than they did before said mao souen a defector from 
the cambodian government army 
